{"title_page": "Communist Youth League of China", "text_new": "{{redirect|Communist Youth League|other Young Communist Leagues|Young Communist League}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{More footnotes|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n| name = Communist Youth League of China\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2}}}}\n| colorcode = Red\n| logo = [[File:China Youth League logo.svg|120px]]\n| logo2 = [[File:China Flag CCYL.svg|150px]]\n| chairperson =\n| secretary2 = He Junke (\u8d3a\u519b\u79d1)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.waonews.com/news/21315-He_Junke_was_elected_the_first_Secretary_of_the_Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Youth_League.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704093044/https://www.waonews.com/news/21315-He_Junke_was_elected_the_first_Secretary_of_the_Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Youth_League.html |archive-date=4 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| founded = 1920, officially 5 May 1922\n| headquarters = No. 10, Qianmen Dongdajie, [[Beijing]]\n| newspaper = ''[[China Youth Daily]]''\n| mother party = [[Communist Party of China]]\n| international = [[Young Communist International]] (Historical)<br>[[World Federation of Democratic Youth]] (Historical)\n| membership= 109 million (by the 17th National Congress)\n| regional1_type =\n| regional1_name =\n| website = {{URL|http://www.ccyl.org.cn/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Communist Youth League of China''', also known as the '''Young Communist League of China''' or simply the '''Communist Youth League''', is a [[youth movement]] of the [[People's Republic of China]] for youth between the ages of fourteen and twenty-eight, run by the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC). The league is organized on the party pattern.{{sfn|Ristaino|1988|p=420}} Its leader is its First Secretary, who is an alternate member of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|CPC Central Committee]]. The current First Secretary (appointed June 2018) is He Junke (born February 1969). The Communist Youth League is responsible also for guiding the activities of the [[Young Pioneers of China|Young Pioneers]] (for children below the age of fifteen).{{sfn|Ristaino|1988|p=421}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Chinese\n|order=st\n|s=\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2\n|t=\u4e2d\u570b\u5171\u7522\u4e3b\u7fa9\u9752\u5e74\u5718\n|p=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 G\u00f2ngch\u01cenzh\u01d4y\u00ec Q\u012bngni\u00e1ntu\u00e1n\n|w=Chung<sup>1</sup>-kuo<sup>2</sup> Kung<sup>4</sup>-ch'an<sup>3</sup>-chu<sup>4</sup>-i<sup>4</sup> Ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-nien<sup>2</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l=Communist Youth League of China\n|altname=Abbreviation\n|s2=\u5171\u9752\u56e2\n|t2=\u5171\u9752\u5718\n|p2=G\u00f2ngq\u012bngtu\u00e1n\n|w2=Kung<sup>4</sup>-ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l2=Communist Youth League\n|altname3=Original name\n|s3=\u4e2d\u56fd\u793e\u4f1a\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2\n|t3=\u4e2d\u570b\u793e\u6703\u4e3b\u7fa9\u9752\u5e74\u5718\n|p3=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 Sh\u00e8hu\u00eczh\u01d4y\u00ec Q\u012bngni\u00e1ntu\u00e1n\n|w3=Chung<sup>1</sup>-kuo<sup>2</sup> She<sup>4</sup>-hui<sup>4</sup>-chu<sup>3</sup>-i<sup>4</sup> Ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-nien<sup>2</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l3=Socialist Youth League of China\n|altname4=Wartime name\n|s4=\u4e2d\u56fd\u65b0\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2\n|t4=\u4e2d\u570b\u65b0\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u7fa9\u9752\u5e74\u5718\n|p4=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 X\u012bn M\u00ednzh\u01d4zh\u01d4y\u00ec Q\u012bngni\u00e1ntu\u00e1n\n|w4=Chung<sup>1</sup>-kuo<sup>2</sup> Hsin<sup>1</sup> Min<sup>2</sup>-chu<sup>3</sup>-chu<sup>3</sup>-i<sup>4</sup> Ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-nien<sup>2</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l4=China New Democracy Youth League\n}}\n\nFounded in May 1920, it was originally named as the '''Socialist Youth League of China'''. Whilst the Party was officially established in July 1921, the Chinese Socialist Youth League was organized with the Party being set up throughout the country. In May 1922, the 1st National Congress ({{zh|s=\u5168\u56fd\u4ee3\u8868\u5927\u4f1a|t=\u5168\u570b\u4ee3\u8868\u5927\u6703|p=Qu\u00e1ngu\u00f3 D\u00e0ibi\u01ceo D\u00e0hu\u00ec}}) of the League was held under the leadership of the Party, and therefore became a unified organization in China. In the 3rd National Congress in January 1925, the Chinese Socialist Youth League was renamed as the Chinese Communist Youth League. After the [[Sino-Japanese War (1937-1945)|Sino-Japanese War]], in order to adapt to the new social and political situation, it was officially renamed as the '''Chinese New Democracy Youth League''' in April 1949.\n\nLater in May 1957, its name as the Chinese Communist Youth League was resumed, historically combining the congresses of all three leagues (the Chinese Socialist Youth League, the Chinese Communist Youth League as well as the Chinese New Democracy Youth League). During the 10 years of the [[Cultural Revolution]], the functioning of the League was blocked and the Central Committee was disbanded as it was accused of revisionism; its functions were partly resumed in the early 1970s. From 1978 to 2008, six congresses were held.\n\nThe Communist Youth League has contributed a number of top echelon leaders of the Communist Party-led government of the People's Republic of China. The proliferation of leaders with a Youth League background has led to the informal name \"[[Tuanpai|Youth League faction]]\" being used to describe certain members of the leadership at different times. The first \"Youth League faction\" was represented by [[Hu Yaobang]] (party chairman 1981-1982, party general secretary 1982-1987 following the abolition of the chairman position). The second \"Youth League faction\" is represented by [[Hu Jintao]] (General secretary 2002-2012, President 2003-2013). While there is no direct political lineage between the two Hus, Hu Jintao's administration has formally elevated the memory of the earlier Hu. In 2005, the 90th anniversary of Hu Yaobang's birth, a new museum and a series of commemorative books and television programs were launched. The [[Ling Jihua#Son's death|scandalous death of the son]] of [[Ling Jihua]] and Gu Liping, a couple associated with the Communist Youth League, may have tarnished the reputation of the organization as a path to power.<ref name=AS03513>{{cite news|title=PREMIER LEAGUE: After fatal Ferrari crash, careers are stalled, group loses power|url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/asia/china/AJ201303050004|accessdate=March 5, 2013|newspaper=The Asahi Shimbun|date=March 5, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308051543/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/asia/china/AJ201303050004|archive-date=8 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCurrent [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] has sought to reduce the prominence of the Communist Party's youth wing, stating that \"All they [cadres] can do is just repeat the same old bureaucratic, stereotypical talk\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2112461/latest-xi-jinping-book-gives-clues-decline-communist?mc_cid=1f9bc1ec42&mc_eid=1f9d28130a |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |title=Latest Xi Jinping book gives clues on decline of Communist Party\u2019s youth wing |date=September 23, 2017 |first=Nectar|last=Gan}}</ref><ref name=\"Nikkei\">{{cite news |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Features/China-up-close/Xi-silences-once-powerful-youth-league-and-former-president-s-protege?mc_cid=1f9bc1ec42&mc_eid=1f9d28130a |newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]] |first=Katsuji |last=Nakazawa |title=Xi silences once-powerful youth league and former president's protege |date=September 25, 2017}}</ref> Political commentators have noted that the diminishing of the [[Tuanpai|Communist Youth League faction]] curtailed the influence of former [[paramount leader]] [[Hu Jintao]], solidifying Xi's own political faction.<ref name=\"Nikkei\"/> Xi effectively closed the Central School of China Communist Youth League, folding it into the [[Chinese Academy of Social Sciences]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\"/> He also demoted the league\u2018s chief and imprisoned one of its top officials.<ref name=\"veconomist\" >{{cite news|author=|title=Xi Jinping has been good for China\u2019s Communist Party; less so for China|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21730138-contradicting-deng-xiaoping-mr-xi-has-concentrated-vast-power-his-own-hands-xi-jinping-has|work=[[The Economist]]|date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Anthem ===\nIn 1987, the first anthem of CYLC was composed.{{vunblist|\"Glorious! Communist Youth League of China\"|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5149\u8363\u554a\uff01\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u9752\u56e2}}}}\n{| cellpadding=\"10\"\n![[Simplified Chinese]]\n{{small|[[Pinyin]]}}\n![[English language|English]] lyrics\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|<poem lang=\"zh-hans\" style=\"font-size:100%\">\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|W\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u662f|sh\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e94|w\u01d4}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6708|yu\u00e8}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u82b1|hu\u0101}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6d77|h\u01cei,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u7528|Y\u00f2ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u9752\u6625|q\u012bngch\u016bn}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u62e5\u62b1|y\u01d2ngb\u00e0o}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u65f6\u4ee3|sh\u00edd\u00e0i;}};\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|W\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u662f|sh\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u521d|ch\u016b}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5347|sh\u0113ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u592a\u9633|t\u00e0iy\u00e1ng,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u7528|Y\u00f2ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u751f\u547d|sh\u0113ngm\u00ecng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u70b9\u71c3|di\u01cenr\u00e1n}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u672a\u6765|w\u00e8il\u00e1i.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e94\u56db|W\u01d4s\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u706b\u70ac|hu\u01d2j\u00f9,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u5524\u8d77\u4e86|Hu\u00e0nq\u01d0le}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6c11\u65cf|m\u00ednz\u00fa}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u89c9\u9192|ju\u00e9x\u01d0ng.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u58ee\u4e3d|Zhu\u00e0ngl\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e8b\u4e1a|sh\u00ecy\u00e8,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6fc0\u52b1\u7740|J\u012bl\u00eczhe}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|w\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7ee7\u5f80\u5f00\u6765|j\u00ecw\u01cengk\u0101il\u00e1i.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u5149\u8363\u554a|Gu\u0101ngr\u00f3ng a,}}\uff0c{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e2d\u56fd|zh\u014dnggu\u00f3}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5171\u9752\u56e2|g\u00f2ngq\u012bngtu\u00e1n,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u5149\u8363\u554a|Gu\u0101ngr\u00f3ng a,}}\uff0c{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e2d\u56fd|zh\u014dnggu\u00f3}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5171\u9752\u56e2|g\u00f2ngq\u012bngtu\u00e1n.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6bcd\u4eb2|M\u01d4q\u012bn}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7528|y\u00f2ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5171\u4ea7|g\u00f2ngch\u01cen}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e3b\u4e49|zh\u01d4y\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e3a|w\u00e8i}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|w\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u547d\u540d|m\u00ecngm\u00edng,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|W\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5f00|k\u0101i}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u521b\u65b0|chu\u00e0ngx\u012bn}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e16\u754c|sh\u00ecji\u00e8.}}\u3002</poem>\n|<poem lang=\"en\" style=\"font-size:100%\">\n\nWe are the flowers of May,\nWho embrace the age of youth;\nWe are the rising sun,\nWho ignites the future with life.\nThe torch of The May Fourth Movement,\nAroused the awakening of the nation.\nA magnificent career,\nInspires us to carry on the future.\nGlorious! Communist Youth League of China,\nGlorious! Communist Youth League of China.\nMother named us with communism.\nWe are creating a new world.\n</poem>\n|}\n\n== Structure ==\nThe national leading organization is the National Congress and the Central Committee, elected by the congresses. The National Congress are held each 5 years, but can be held earlier or later under special circumstances. In between congresses, the Central Committee implements the decisions made in the National Congress and leads the League as a whole; the Central Committee usually meets in plenary session once a year. In addition to the Central Committee, there are General Affairs Committees which oversee the daily affairs of the League and lead the fundamental organizations in 31 provincial level administrative areas of the country. \"CPC and is considered to be the CPC's assistant and backup\".<ref name=\"chinadaily2007\">[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2007-05/04/content_865669.htm China's Communist Youth League has 73.496 million members]. Chinadaily.com.cn (4 May 2007).</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2002, there were approximately 210,000 committee members of fundamental organizations. 2007 estimates put the number of Youth League members at 73 million.<ref>Xinhua News Agency, [http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200705/05/print20070505_372030.html \u201cChina\u2019s Communist Youth League has 73.496 million members\u201d], 4 May 2007.</ref> Central Committee reported at the end of 2006, students accounted for 49.9% of the league.<ref name=\"chinadaily2007\"/>\n\nUnder the leadership of Communist Party General Secretary [[Hu Jintao]], who was also a leading figure in the Youth League, key government positions at both central and provincial levels are more likely to be filled by the League's members and former cadres, known as ''tuanpai''.\n\nCYLC's official newspaper is the ''[[China Youth Daily]]''.\n\n== List of First Secretaries ==\n*[[Yu Xiusong]] (\u4fde\u79c0\u677e): 1920\u20131922\n*[[Shi Cuntong]] (\u65bd\u5b58\u7edf): 1922\u20131925\n*[[Zhang Tailei]] (\u5f20\u592a\u96f7): 1925\u20131927\n*[[Ren Bishi]] (\u4efb\u5f3c\u65f6): 1927\u20131928\n*[[Guan Xiangying]] (\u5173\u5411\u5e94): 1928\u20131946\n*[[Feng Wenbin]] (\u99ae\u6587\u5f6c): 1949\u20131953\n*[[Hu Yaobang]] (\u80e1\u8000\u90a6): 1953\u20131978\n*[[Han Ying]] (\u97e9\u82f1): 1978\u20131982\n*[[Wang Zhaoguo]] (\u738b\u5146\u56fd): 1982\u20131984\n*[[Hu Jintao]] (\u80e1\u9526\u6d9b): 1984\u20131985\n*[[Song Defu]] (\u5b8b\u5fb7\u798f): 1985\u20131993\n*[[Li Keqiang]] (\u674e\u514b\u5f3a): 1993\u20131998\n*[[Zhou Qiang]] (\u5468\u5f3a): 1998\u20132006\n*[[Hu Chunhua]] (\u80e1\u6625\u534e): 2006\u20132008\n*[[Lu Hao (born 1967)|Lu Hao]] (\u9646\u660a): 2008\u20132013\n*[[Qin Yizhi]] (\u79e6\u5b9c\u667a): 2013\u20132017\n*[[He Junke]] (\u8d3a\u519b\u79d1): 2018\u2013\n\n== Chronology of National Congresses ==\n*1st National Congress (Socialist Youth League): 5\u201310 May 1922\n*2nd National Congress (Socialist Youth League): 2\u201325 August 1923\n*3rd National Congress (Socialist Youth League): 26\u201330 January 1925\n*4th National Congress: 10\u201316 May 1927\n*5th National Congress: 12\u201316 July 1928\n*6th National Congress (1st Congress, New Democratic Youth League): 11\u201318 April 1949\n*7th National Congress (2nd Congress, New Democratic Youth League): 23 June\u20132 July 1953\n*8th National Congress (3rd Congress, New Democratic Youth League): 12\u201325 May 1957\n*9th National Congress: 11\u201329 June 1964\n*10th National Congress: 16\u201326 October 1978\n*11th National Congress: 20\u201330 December 1982\n*12th National Congress: 4\u20138 May 1988\n*13th National Congress: 3\u201310 May 1993\n*14th National Congress: 19\u201325 June 1998\n*15th National Congress: 22\u201326 July 2003\n*16th National Congress: 10\u201313 June 2008\n*17th National Congress: 17\u201321 June 2013\n*18th National Congress: 26\u201329  June 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://h.bilibili.com/4950980|title=micro-blog of Communist Youth League of China}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Young Communist League]]\n*[[Communist Party of China]]\n*[[Young Pioneers of China]]\n*[[Komsomol]]\n*[[Kim Il-sung Youth League]]\n*[[Tuanpai]]\n*[[China Youth University for Political Sciences]]\n*[[All-China Federation of Trade Unions]]\n*[[All-China Women's Federation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Attribution===\n*{{Country study|country=China|abbr=cn|editor-last1=Worden|editor-first1=Robert L.|editor-last2=Savada|editor-first2=Andrea Matles|editor-last3=Dolan|editor-first3=Ronald E.|date=1988|section=\"Party and Government\", pp. 407\u2013442|last=Ristaino|first=Marcia R.|pd=yes<!-- yes/no - no removes the notice about pd text -->|ref=harv|edition=Fourth|oclc=232918611}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ccyl.org.cn/}}\n* [http://www.cycnet.com/ Site for the general youth, promoting things such as patriotism, youth employment and  volunteerism]\n{{Communist youth wings}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Communist Youth League Of China}}\n[[Category:Youth organizations based in China]]\n[[Category:Youth wings of communist parties]]\n[[Category:Youth wings of political parties in China]]\n[[Category:Communist Youth League of China| ]]\n[[Category:Youth organizations established in 1920]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Communist Youth League|other Young Communist Leagues|Young Communist League}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{More footnotes|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n|name = Communist Youth League of China<br>{{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2}}}}\n|native_name = \n|colorcode = red\n|logo = [[File:China Youth League logo.svg|120px]]\n|logo2=[[Image:China Flag CCYL.svg|150px]]\n|chairperson =\n|secretary2 = He Junke(\u8d3a\u519b\u79d1)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.waonews.com/news/21315-He_Junke_was_elected_the_first_Secretary_of_the_Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Youth_League.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704093044/https://www.waonews.com/news/21315-He_Junke_was_elected_the_first_Secretary_of_the_Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Youth_League.html |archive-date=4 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|founded = 1920, officially 5 May 1922\n|headquarters = No. 10, Qianmen Dongdajie, [[Beijing]]\n|newspaper = ''[[China Youth Daily]]''\n|mother party = [[Communist Party of China]]\n|international = [[Young Communist International]] (Historical)<br>[[World Federation of Democratic Youth]] (Historical)\n|membership= 109 million (by the 17th National Congress)\n|regional1_type =\n|regional1_name = \n|website = {{URL|http://www.ccyl.org.cn/}}\n}}\nThe '''Communist Youth League of China''', also known as the '''Young Communist League of China''' or simply the '''Communist Youth League''', is a [[youth movement]] of the [[People's Republic of China]] for youth between the ages of fourteen and twenty-eight, run by the [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC). The league is organized on the party pattern.{{sfn|Ristaino|1988|p=420}} Its leader is its First Secretary, who is an alternate member of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|CPC Central Committee]]. The current First Secretary (appointed June 2018) is He Junke (born February 1969). The Communist Youth League is responsible also for guiding the activities of the [[Young Pioneers of China|Young Pioneers]] (for children below the age of fifteen).{{sfn|Ristaino|1988|p=421}}\n\n== History ==\n{{Chinese\n|order=st\n|s=\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u4ea7\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2\n|t=\u4e2d\u570b\u5171\u7522\u4e3b\u7fa9\u9752\u5e74\u5718\n|p=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 G\u00f2ngch\u01cenzh\u01d4y\u00ec Q\u012bngni\u00e1ntu\u00e1n\n|w=Chung<sup>1</sup>-kuo<sup>2</sup> Kung<sup>4</sup>-ch'an<sup>3</sup>-chu<sup>4</sup>-i<sup>4</sup> Ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-nien<sup>2</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l=Communist Youth League of China\n|altname=Abbreviation\n|s2=\u5171\u9752\u56e2\n|t2=\u5171\u9752\u5718\n|p2=G\u00f2ngq\u012bngtu\u00e1n\n|w2=Kung<sup>4</sup>-ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l2=Communist Youth League\n|altname3=Original name\n|s3=\u4e2d\u56fd\u793e\u4f1a\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2\n|t3=\u4e2d\u570b\u793e\u6703\u4e3b\u7fa9\u9752\u5e74\u5718\n|p3=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 Sh\u00e8hu\u00eczh\u01d4y\u00ec Q\u012bngni\u00e1ntu\u00e1n\n|w3=Chung<sup>1</sup>-kuo<sup>2</sup> She<sup>4</sup>-hui<sup>4</sup>-chu<sup>3</sup>-i<sup>4</sup> Ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-nien<sup>2</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l3=Socialist Youth League of China\n|altname4=Wartime name\n|s4=\u4e2d\u56fd\u65b0\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u4e49\u9752\u5e74\u56e2\n|t4=\u4e2d\u570b\u65b0\u6c11\u4e3b\u4e3b\u7fa9\u9752\u5e74\u5718\n|p4=Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 X\u012bn M\u00ednzh\u01d4zh\u01d4y\u00ec Q\u012bngni\u00e1ntu\u00e1n\n|w4=Chung<sup>1</sup>-kuo<sup>2</sup> Hsin<sup>1</sup> Min<sup>2</sup>-chu<sup>3</sup>-chu<sup>3</sup>-i<sup>4</sup> Ch'ing<sup>1</sup>-nien<sup>2</sup>-t'uan<sup>2</sup>\n|l4=China New Democracy Youth League\n}}\n\nFounded in May 1920, it was originally named as the '''Socialist Youth League of China'''. Whilst the Party was officially established in July 1921, the Chinese Socialist Youth League was organized with the Party being set up throughout the country. In May 1922, the 1st National Congress ({{zh|s=\u5168\u56fd\u4ee3\u8868\u5927\u4f1a|t=\u5168\u570b\u4ee3\u8868\u5927\u6703|p=Qu\u00e1ngu\u00f3 D\u00e0ibi\u01ceo D\u00e0hu\u00ec}}) of the League was held under the leadership of the Party, and therefore became a unified organization in China. In the 3rd National Congress in January 1925, the Chinese Socialist Youth League was renamed as the Chinese Communist Youth League. After the [[Sino-Japanese War (1937-1945)|Sino-Japanese War]], in order to adapt to the new social and political situation, it was officially renamed as the '''Chinese New Democracy Youth League''' in April 1949.\n\nLater in May 1957, its name as the Chinese Communist Youth League was resumed, historically combining the congresses of all three leagues (the Chinese Socialist Youth League, the Chinese Communist Youth League as well as the Chinese New Democracy Youth League). During the 10 years of the [[Cultural Revolution]], the functioning of the League was blocked and the Central Committee was disbanded as it was accused of revisionism; its functions were partly resumed in the early 1970s. From 1978 to 2008, six congresses were held.\n\nThe Communist Youth League has contributed a number of top echelon leaders of the Communist Party-led government of the People's Republic of China. The proliferation of leaders with a Youth League background has led to the informal name \"[[Tuanpai|Youth League faction]]\" being used to describe certain members of the leadership at different times. The first \"Youth League faction\" was represented by [[Hu Yaobang]] (party chairman 1981-1982, party general secretary 1982-1987 following the abolition of the chairman position). The second \"Youth League faction\" is represented by [[Hu Jintao]] (General secretary 2002-2012, President 2003-2013). While there is no direct political lineage between the two Hus, Hu Jintao's administration has formally elevated the memory of the earlier Hu. In 2005, the 90th anniversary of Hu Yaobang's birth, a new museum and a series of commemorative books and television programs were launched. The [[Ling Jihua#Son's death|scandalous death of the son]] of [[Ling Jihua]] and Gu Liping, a couple associated with the Communist Youth League, may have tarnished the reputation of the organization as a path to power.<ref name=AS03513>{{cite news|title=PREMIER LEAGUE: After fatal Ferrari crash, careers are stalled, group loses power|url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/asia/china/AJ201303050004|accessdate=March 5, 2013|newspaper=The Asahi Shimbun|date=March 5, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308051543/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/asia/china/AJ201303050004|archive-date=8 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCurrent [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] has sought to reduce the prominence of the Communist Party's youth wing, stating that \"All they [cadres] can do is just repeat the same old bureaucratic, stereotypical talk\".<ref name=\"SCMP\">{{cite news |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2112461/latest-xi-jinping-book-gives-clues-decline-communist?mc_cid=1f9bc1ec42&mc_eid=1f9d28130a |newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] |title=Latest Xi Jinping book gives clues on decline of Communist Party\u2019s youth wing |date=September 23, 2017 |first=Nectar|last=Gan}}</ref><ref name=\"Nikkei\">{{cite news |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Features/China-up-close/Xi-silences-once-powerful-youth-league-and-former-president-s-protege?mc_cid=1f9bc1ec42&mc_eid=1f9d28130a |newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]] |first=Katsuji |last=Nakazawa |title=Xi silences once-powerful youth league and former president's protege |date=September 25, 2017}}</ref> Political commentators have noted that the diminishing of the [[Tuanpai|Communist Youth League faction]] curtailed the influence of former [[paramount leader]] [[Hu Jintao]], solidifying Xi's own political faction.<ref name=\"Nikkei\"/> Xi effectively closed the Central School of China Communist Youth League, folding it into the [[Chinese Academy of Social Sciences]].<ref name=\"Nikkei\"/> He also demoted the league\u2018s chief and imprisoned one of its top officials.<ref name=\"veconomist\" >{{cite news|author=|title=Xi Jinping has been good for China\u2019s Communist Party; less so for China|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21730138-contradicting-deng-xiaoping-mr-xi-has-concentrated-vast-power-his-own-hands-xi-jinping-has|work=[[The Economist]]|date=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Anthem ===\nIn 1987, the first anthem of CYLC was composed.{{vunblist|\"Glorious! Communist Youth League of China\"|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5149\u8363\u554a\uff01\u4e2d\u56fd\u5171\u9752\u56e2}}}}\n{| cellpadding=\"10\"\n![[Simplified Chinese]]\n{{small|[[Pinyin]]}}\n![[English language|English]] lyrics\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|<poem lang=\"zh-hans\" style=\"font-size:100%\">\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|W\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u662f|sh\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e94|w\u01d4}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6708|yu\u00e8}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u82b1|hu\u0101}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6d77|h\u01cei,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u7528|Y\u00f2ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u9752\u6625|q\u012bngch\u016bn}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u62e5\u62b1|y\u01d2ngb\u00e0o}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u65f6\u4ee3|sh\u00edd\u00e0i;}};\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|W\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u662f|sh\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u521d|ch\u016b}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5347|sh\u0113ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u592a\u9633|t\u00e0iy\u00e1ng,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u7528|Y\u00f2ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u751f\u547d|sh\u0113ngm\u00ecng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u70b9\u71c3|di\u01cenr\u00e1n}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u672a\u6765|w\u00e8il\u00e1i.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e94\u56db|W\u01d4s\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u706b\u70ac|hu\u01d2j\u00f9,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u5524\u8d77\u4e86|Hu\u00e0nq\u01d0le}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6c11\u65cf|m\u00ednz\u00fa}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u89c9\u9192|ju\u00e9x\u01d0ng.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u58ee\u4e3d|Zhu\u00e0ngl\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e8b\u4e1a|sh\u00ecy\u00e8,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6fc0\u52b1\u7740|J\u012bl\u00eczhe}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|w\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7ee7\u5f80\u5f00\u6765|j\u00ecw\u01cengk\u0101il\u00e1i.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u5149\u8363\u554a|Gu\u0101ngr\u00f3ng a,}}\uff0c{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e2d\u56fd|zh\u014dnggu\u00f3}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5171\u9752\u56e2|g\u00f2ngq\u012bngtu\u00e1n,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u5149\u8363\u554a|Gu\u0101ngr\u00f3ng a,}}\uff0c{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e2d\u56fd|zh\u014dnggu\u00f3}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5171\u9752\u56e2|g\u00f2ngq\u012bngtu\u00e1n.}}\u3002\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6bcd\u4eb2|M\u01d4q\u012bn}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7528|y\u00f2ng}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5171\u4ea7|g\u00f2ngch\u01cen}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e3b\u4e49|zh\u01d4y\u00ec}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e3a|w\u00e8i}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|w\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u547d\u540d|m\u00ecngm\u00edng,}}\uff0c\n{{ruby-zh-p|\u6211\u4eec|W\u01d2men}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u5f00|k\u0101i}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u521b\u65b0|chu\u00e0ngx\u012bn}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u7684|de}}{{ruby-zh-p|\u4e16\u754c|sh\u00ecji\u00e8.}}\u3002</poem>\n|<poem lang=\"en\" style=\"font-size:100%\">\n\nWe are the flowers of May,\nWho embrace the age of youth;\nWe are the rising sun,\nWho ignites the future with life.\nThe torch of The May Fourth Movement,\nAroused the awakening of the nation.\nA magnificent career,\nInspires us to carry on the future.\nGlorious! Communist Youth League of China,\nGlorious! Communist Youth League of China.\nMother named us with communism.\nWe are creating a new world.\n</poem>\n|}\n\n== Structure ==\nThe national leading organization is the National Congress and the Central Committee, elected by the congresses. The National Congress are held each 5 years, but can be held earlier or later under special circumstances. In between congresses, the Central Committee implements the decisions made in the National Congress and leads the League as a whole; the Central Committee usually meets in plenary session once a year. In addition to the Central Committee, there are General Affairs Committees which oversee the daily affairs of the League and lead the fundamental organizations in 31 provincial level administrative areas of the country. \"CPC and is considered to be the CPC's assistant and backup\".<ref name=\"chinadaily2007\">[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2007-05/04/content_865669.htm China's Communist Youth League has 73.496 million members]. Chinadaily.com.cn (4 May 2007).</ref>\n\nBy the end of 2002, there were approximately 210,000 committee members of fundamental organizations. 2007 estimates put the number of Youth League members at 73 million.<ref>Xinhua News Agency, [http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200705/05/print20070505_372030.html \u201cChina\u2019s Communist Youth League has 73.496 million members\u201d], 4 May 2007.</ref> Central Committee reported at the end of 2006, students accounted for 49.9% of the league.<ref name=\"chinadaily2007\"/>\n\nUnder the leadership of Communist Party General Secretary [[Hu Jintao]], who was also a leading figure in the Youth League, key government positions at both central and provincial levels are more likely to be filled by the League's members and former cadres, known as ''tuanpai''.\n\nCYLC's official newspaper is the ''[[China Youth Daily]]''.\n\n== List of First Secretaries ==\n*[[Yu Xiusong]] (\u4fde\u79c0\u677e): 1920\u20131922\n*[[Shi Cuntong]] (\u65bd\u5b58\u7edf): 1922\u20131925\n*[[Zhang Tailei]] (\u5f20\u592a\u96f7): 1925\u20131927\n*[[Ren Bishi]] (\u4efb\u5f3c\u65f6): 1927\u20131928\n*[[Guan Xiangying]] (\u5173\u5411\u5e94): 1928\u20131946\n*[[Feng Wenbin]] (\u99ae\u6587\u5f6c): 1949\u20131953\n*[[Hu Yaobang]] (\u80e1\u8000\u90a6): 1953\u20131978\n*[[Han Ying]] (\u97e9\u82f1): 1978\u20131982\n*[[Wang Zhaoguo]] (\u738b\u5146\u56fd): 1982\u20131984\n*[[Hu Jintao]] (\u80e1\u9526\u6d9b): 1984\u20131985\n*[[Song Defu]] (\u5b8b\u5fb7\u798f): 1985\u20131993\n*[[Li Keqiang]] (\u674e\u514b\u5f3a): 1993\u20131998\n*[[Zhou Qiang]] (\u5468\u5f3a): 1998\u20132006\n*[[Hu Chunhua]] (\u80e1\u6625\u534e): 2006\u20132008\n*[[Lu Hao (born 1967)|Lu Hao]] (\u9646\u660a): 2008\u20132013\n*[[Qin Yizhi]] (\u79e6\u5b9c\u667a): 2013\u20132017\n*[[He Junke]] (\u8d3a\u519b\u79d1): 2018\u2013\n\n== Chronology of National Congresses ==\n*1st National Congress (Socialist Youth League): 5\u201310 May 1922\n*2nd National Congress (Socialist Youth League): 2\u201325 August 1923\n*3rd National Congress (Socialist Youth League): 26\u201330 January 1925\n*4th National Congress: 10\u201316 May 1927\n*5th National Congress: 12\u201316 July 1928\n*6th National Congress (1st Congress, New Democratic Youth League): 11\u201318 April 1949\n*7th National Congress (2nd Congress, New Democratic Youth League): 23 June\u20132 July 1953\n*8th National Congress (3rd Congress, New Democratic Youth League): 12\u201325 May 1957\n*9th National Congress: 11\u201329 June 1964\n*10th National Congress: 16\u201326 October 1978\n*11th National Congress: 20\u201330 December 1982\n*12th National Congress: 4\u20138 May 1988\n*13th National Congress: 3\u201310 May 1993\n*14th National Congress: 19\u201325 June 1998\n*15th National Congress: 22\u201326 July 2003\n*16th National Congress: 10\u201313 June 2008\n*17th National Congress: 17\u201321 June 2013\n*18th National Congress: 26\u201329  June 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://h.bilibili.com/4950980|title=micro-blog of Communist Youth League of China}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Young Communist League]]\n*[[Communist Party of China]]\n*[[Young Pioneers of China]]\n*[[Komsomol]]\n*[[Kim Il-sung Youth League]]\n*[[Tuanpai]]\n*[[China Youth University for Political Sciences]]\n*[[All-China Federation of Trade Unions]]\n*[[All-China Women's Federation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Attribution===\n*{{Country study|country=China|abbr=cn|editor-last1=Worden|editor-first1=Robert L.|editor-last2=Savada|editor-first2=Andrea Matles|editor-last3=Dolan|editor-first3=Ronald E.|date=1988|section=\"Party and Government\", pp. 407\u2013442|last=Ristaino|first=Marcia R.|pd=yes<!-- yes/no - no removes the notice about pd text -->|ref=harv|edition=Fourth|oclc=232918611}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.ccyl.org.cn/}}\n* [http://www.cycnet.com/ Site for the general youth, promoting things such as patriotism, youth employment and  volunteerism]\n{{Communist youth wings}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Communist Youth League Of China}}\n[[Category:Youth organizations based in China]]\n[[Category:Youth wings of communist parties]]\n[[Category:Youth wings of political parties in China]]\n[[Category:Communist Youth League of China| ]]\n[[Category:Youth organizations established in 1920]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in China]]\n", "name_user": "CentreLeftRight", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Communist_Youth_League_of_China"}
{"title_page": "The Purple Vigilantes", "text_new": "{{short description|1938 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Purple Vigilantes\n| image          = The Purple Vigilantes FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[George Sherman]]\n| producer       = [[Sol C. Siegel]]\n| writer         = [[William Colt MacDonald]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Betty Burbridge]]\n* [[Oliver Drake (filmmaker)|Oliver Drake]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]]\n* [[Ray Corrigan]]\n* [[Max Terhune]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alberto Colombo (composer)|Alberto Colombo]]\n| cinematography = [[Ernest Miller (cinematographer)|Ernest Miller]]\n| editing        = Lester Orlebeck\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Republic Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1938|01|24}}\n| runtime        = 58 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''The Purple Vigilantes''''' is a 1938 American [[Western (genre)|Western]] film directed by [[George Sherman]] and starring [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]], [[Ray Corrigan]], and [[Max Terhune]]. Written by [[Betty Burbridge]] and [[Oliver Drake (filmmaker)|Oliver Drake]], the film is about a rancher who organizes other ranchers to form a vigilante group in order to rid their town of outlaws. After the outlaws are defeated, some of the men, posing as the vigilant group, go on a crime spree. ''The Purple Vigilantes'' is the 12th entry in the ''[[The Three Mesquiteers|Three Mesquiteers]]'' series of [[B-movie]]s produced by [[Republic Pictures]].<ref name=\"b-westerns\">{{cite web |url=http://www.b-westerns.com/trio3m7.htm |title=The Three Mesquiteers Republic Pictures |publisher=b-westerns.com |accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref> The film was released in the United Kingdom as '''''Purple Riders''''' because at that time the word \"vigilante\" was unknown in Britain.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=Phil|title=The BFI Companion to Crime|date=1997|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780304332151|page=340|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=agfHUakbj5kC&pg=PA340|accessdate=October 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nJohn Denvir, in his book, ''Legal Reelism: Movies as Legal Texts'', compared the hooded-and-robed vigilantes in the film to the [[Ku Klux Klan]]. He cited ''The Purple Vigilantes'' as being \"the series western most clearly inspired by the Klan\", noting that the film was \"treating its hooded terrorist organization as originally serving a legitimate purpose but corrupted over time.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Denvir|first1=John|title=Legal Reelism: Movies as Legal Texts|date=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=9780252065354|page=[https://archive.org/details/legalreelismmovi00denv/page/68 68]|url=https://archive.org/details/legalreelismmovi00denv|url-access=registration|accessdate=October 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]] as Stony Brooke\n* [[Ray Corrigan]] as Tucson Smith\n* [[Max Terhune]] as Lullaby Joslin\n* [[Joan Barclay]] as Jean McAllister\n* [[Earl Dwire]] as David Ross\n* [[Earle Hodgins]] as J. T. McAllister\n* [[Francis Sayles]] as Wiliam Jones\n* [[George Chesebro]] as Eggers\n* [[Robert Fiske (actor)|Robert Fiske]] as George Drake\n* [[Jack Perrin]] as Duncan\n* [[Ernie Adams (actor)|Ernie Adams]] as Blake\n* [[William Gould (actor)|William Gould]] as Jenkins, Saloon Owner\n* [[Harry Strang]] as Murphy\n* Ed Cassidy as Sheriff Jim (as Edward Cassidy)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0030636|title=The Purple Vigilantes}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RXHEbzxT7Rc ''The Purple Vigilantes'' on YouTube]\n\n{{George Sherman}}\n{{The Three Mesquiteers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purple Vigilantes}}\n[[Category:1938 films]]\n[[Category:1938 Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George Sherman]]\n[[Category:Republic Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Three Mesquiteers films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Sol C. Siegel]]\n\n\n{{1930s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1938 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Purple Vigilantes\n| image          = The Purple Vigilantes FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[George Sherman]]\n| producer       = [[Sol C. Siegel]]\n| writer         = [[William Colt MacDonald]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Betty Burbridge]]\n* [[Oliver Drake (filmmaker)|Oliver Drake]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]]\n* [[Ray Corrigan]]\n* [[Max Terhune]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alberto Colombo (composer)|Alberto Colombo]]\n| cinematography = [[Ernest Miller (cinematographer)|Ernest Miller]]\n| editing        = Lester Orlebeck\n| studio         = \n| distributor    = [[Republic Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1938|01|24}}\n| runtime        = 58 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''The Purple Vigilantes''''' is a 1938 American [[Western (genre)|Western]] film directed by [[George Sherman]] and starring [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]], [[Ray Corrigan]], and [[Max Terhune]]. Written by [[Betty Burbridge]] and [[Oliver Drake (filmmaker)|Oliver Drake]], the film is about a rancher who organizes other ranchers to form a vigilante group in order to rid their town of outlaws. After the outlaws are defeated, some of the men, posing as the vigilant group, go on a crime spree. ''The Purple Vigilantes'' is the 12th entry in the ''[[The Three Mesquiteers|Three Mesquiteers]]'' series of [[B-movie]]s produced by [[Republic Pictures]].<ref name=\"b-westerns\">{{cite web |url=http://www.b-westerns.com/trio3m7.htm |title=The Three Mesquiteers Republic Pictures |publisher=b-westerns.com |accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref> The film was released in the United Kingdom as '''''Purple Riders''''' because at that time the word \"vigilante\" was unknown in Britain.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=Phil|title=The BFI Companion to Crime|date=1997|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780304332151|page=340|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=agfHUakbj5kC&pg=PA340|accessdate=October 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nJohn Denvir, in his book, ''Legal Reelism: Movies as Legal Texts'', compared the hooded-and-robed vigilantes in the film to the [[Ku Klux Klan]]. He cited ''The Purple Vigilantes'' as being \"the series western most clearly inspired by the Klan\", noting that the film was \"treating its hooded terrorist organization as originally serving a legitimate purpose but corrupted over time.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Denvir|first1=John|title=Legal Reelism: Movies as Legal Texts|date=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=9780252065354|page=[https://archive.org/details/legalreelismmovi00denv/page/68 68]|url=https://archive.org/details/legalreelismmovi00denv|url-access=registration|accessdate=October 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Robert Livingston (actor)|Robert Livingston]] as Stony Brooke\n* [[Ray Corrigan]] as Tucson Smith\n* [[Max Terhune]] as Lullaby Joslin\n* [[Joan Barclay]] as Jean McAllister\n* [[Earl Dwire]] as David Ross\n* [[Earle Hodgins]] as J. T. McAllister\n* [[Francis Sayles]] as Wiliam Jones\n* [[George Chesebro]] as Eggers\n* [[Robert Fiske (actor)|Robert Fiske]] as George Drake\n* [[Jack Perrin]] as Duncan\n* [[Ernie Adams (actor)|Ernie Adams]] as Blake\n* [[William Gould (actor)|William Gould]] as Jenkins, Saloon Owner\n* [[Harry Strang]] as Murphy\n* Ed Cassidy as Sheriff Jim (as Edward Cassidy)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0030636|title=The Purple Vigilantes}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RXHEbzxT7Rc ''The Purple Vigilantes'' on YouTube]\n\n{{George Sherman}}\n{{The Three Mesquiteers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purple Vigilantes}}\n[[Category:1938 films]]\n[[Category:1938 Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George Sherman]]\n[[Category:Republic Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Three Mesquiteers films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Sol C. Siegel]]\n\n\n{{1930s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Purple_Vigilantes"}
